We recommended and Management agreed, through the MDRRMO, to:
a. revisit the guidelines relative to the utilization of the LDRRMF to ensure and enforce the strict compliance thereof;
b. review and assess the projects, programs and activities with respect to their compliance with existing laws, rules and regulations as a requirement before these undertakings are endeavored to form part of the LDRRMFIP;
c. identify projects, programs and activities, with a view of the funding constraints, by assessing which to prioritize and implement vis-à-vis the LGU determined disaster related issues;
d. review the guidelines in updating the LDRRMFIP to ensure that relevant measures are properly observed. Likewise, evaluate the compliance of the LGU as regards the realignment procedures to warrant that the legislation enacted is sufficient and appropriate with what has been required by the law;
e. refrain from accommodating expenditures which do not fall within the recommended programs, projects and activities chargeable against the LDRRMF; and
f. develop and implement measures to make the processes of disbursements more transparent by adhering as much as possible to the law, rules and regulations.

We also recommended and Management agreed, through Municipal Accountant, to:
a. strengthen the controls being adopted pertaining to the proper identification and recording of transactions by diligently reviewing the nature and purpose of each transaction in order to reflect their true and correct balances; and
b. draw the necessary adjusting journal entries, in view of the preceding discussions and/or presentation in order to facilitate the proper classification of transactions to their proper accounts.

We recommended the following:
1. Address the Accounting Department to:
a. Maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network;
b. Prepare/maintain the Local Road Network Ledger Card;
c. Prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year; and
d. Disclose the total network system in the Notes to the Financial Statements.
2. Require the General Services Office to:
a. Maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map;
b. Keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;
c. Prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System; and
d. Render a Report on Local Road Network of the LGU at the end of the accounting period.
3. Direct the Municipal Engineering Office to provide the accounting office and the general services office with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects.

In order to address the observations and increase collections, we recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:
1. Improve revenue forecasting by using the forecasting tools provided by the Bureau of Local Government Finance (BLGF);
2. Institute periodic review and assessment during the year to ascertain whether collection targets are attained. The reasons for the shortfall in collections should be analyzed and alternative actions should be looked into to improve revenue projections;
3. Inspect business establishments within the jurisdiction of the Municipality to ensure effective and efficient collection of business taxes as mandated under [Section 470 (d)(4)] of LGC;
4. Maintain and update the tax information system of the Municipality thru:
 establishing a tax roll for each type of tax and revenue imposed in the Revenue Code;
 conduct of tax census and develop revenue data bank; and
 a systematic and organized records of payments of all taxpayers.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:
1. Municipal Treasurer to prepare and furnish the Certified List of Taxpayers and tax due and collectible;
2. Municipal Accountant to (i) base the establishment of RPT and SET Receivables on the list submitted by the Treasury Office; (ii) trace and record the adjustments to reconcile the differences between the amount of the recorded RPT and SET Receivables; and (iii) maintain subsidiary ledgers of real property taxpayers based on the certified list of real property taxpayers.

We recommended and Management concurred to:
1. Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal GSO to maintain the PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively for each item as control records and to facilitate the regular reconciliation of records. This should be given utmost importance to determine the accuracy and reliability of the PPE account balances at year-end;
2. Initiate the immediate disposal of the assets unserviceable, if any, in accordance with Section 79 of PD 1445 to avoid further deterioration.

